narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This is one of those courses that you will learn real skills that are applicable to so many aspects of academics. Learning how to code in R and make compelling visualizations will prove useful at times and places you never expected. If you are completely knew to coding, have a friend explain the basics to you before you start the course, or meet with the TAs to gain a solid foundation.
How to graph using ggplot and syntax of R
This course gave us a lot of insight into what makes good data visualizations. In addition, it gave us a thorough understanding of ggplot and tidyverse.
r
History and principles of data visualization, intersection of data visualization and art, use of ggplot2 in R to create data visualizations, what makes a graph good/bad

In this class, the syllabus says you learn about 5 things, and it is mostly correct. History of Data Visualization, Theory of Data Visualization, Modern Art, Making Data Visualizations with the R package ggplot2, and visualizing social data. I feel I learned really interesting things about each of the topics, with particular emphasis put on ggplot2, and theory and history of data visualization. I came into the class knowing vaguely how to make basic histograms in R, and left with the ability to think of and produce all sorts of actually good graphs, as well as data maps, in ggplot2. Moreover, the class showed me how data visualization is not a recourse to be used when you need a powerpoint, but a core tool in truly understanding data and the world. I also learned some interesting things about history, art and political science. I think it would be incredibly useful to anyone interested in statistics, political science or other social sciences.

I learned the basics of data tidying in R and how to use the "grammar of graphics" through ggplot. I also learned how to more thoroughly analyze graphs, as well as the power that visualizations have on conveying a lot of information in little space. The final project also allowed me to craft an original argument through research, data, and graphs, which I think combines a lot of important skills into one final product.
A solid, transferable foundation for visualization in R/ggplot2! Some interesting tidbits about the history of data viz too.
Greater knowledge of R and ggplot2.

I learned how to use ggplot2 in R (and how to use R!) I also learned about the history of visualizations which was cool, as well as good practices for how to make a good visualization  which is very important for my work in the future. However, I did not learn a lot. I came into this class knowing no ggplot2 and no R. And I left knowing a little bit, with some big holes in my knowledge. There are some very basic concepts I still dont understand. Part of the reason why is my fault. You did not need to do the readings to get 100% on the psets. And Im busy. So I never did the readings. And that bit me in the a** because I am leaving this class not as strong as I should. That being said, I think the psets should have pushed us a bit harder and really forced us to practice and explore things like mutate and piping and such (without it being handed to us in the example portion of the pset).

I began the course with 0 experience with R and/or coding, and ended feeling very comfortable using it and excited to learn more languages! I learned how to create countless types of visualizations, how to imagine data in different ways, and how to use ggplot to create dynamic visualizations I never could have imagined creating before taking this course!

Most important and major skillshow to use ggplot! This is a fantastic course that teaches practical skills about creating data visualizations (bar charts, line, and MUCH more) in ggplot, something that I will most likely use in other contexts as well. Other insights included artistic principles of visualization, and interesting historical case studies including WEB DuBois, Florence Nightingale, Agnes Martin and Maya Lin. I was challenged to think about what could be considered as data visualization beyond standard line graphs! Overall, this is pretty much what you expect from a class all about data visualization, with a few surprising and creative extras added on!
Topics in data visualization (and how to use ggplot)
Good command of ggplot2.

coding in R 
critically evaluating data viz in the media
Learned ggplot and history/theory/good practices for data visualization
how to visualise data with ggplot package

The course is extremely useful for anyone entering any type of research field. At this classs very core, we delve into what makes certain data visualizations bad communicators of data and how to create better ones using ggplot. Even though this class is listed as a political science course, the assignments allowed us to stray into what we are most interested in, which allows us to smooth out the complications that arise from taking what we learned as a class and manipulating the code to serve our own individual projects.

In addition to learning how to code in GGPlot, I also developed my creative thinking abilities by taking this class. It was a refreshing break from the other primarily analytical classes and taught me how to harness the visualization of data to address important problems in the social sciences and beyond. I also learned about the fascinating history of visualizations as well as what makes a "good" or "bad" graph.

Learned about data visualization theory, history, tidyverse/ggplot2, intersection of art and data visualization, ways to visualize political/social data. The theory/history portion is centered around Edward Tufte's influential work *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* though we do challenge and critique the principles Tufte outlines at times. Most S&DS professors I've worked with up until this point use base R rather than the tidyverse. I think it would have been nice to learn a little more about the tidyverse philosophywhat are its advantages? Why are dollar signs bad? Without the motivation, I'm probably going to continue coding in base R.
Through taking this course, I was exposed to the basics of R, and specifically ggplot2. it was a great introductory-level class for someone like me who had no prior experience with R.
Data visualization skills! Artistic abstraction. Theories of designing graphs.
I gained insight into best practices for visualizing data, as well as how to do it in R using the ggplot package.

I developed proficiency in basic ggPlot graphics. For any type of non-animated graphic I might want to make (and for most simple data sets), I can now independently make that graphic (or, at least, understand online documentation which explains how to make that type of graphic).

I have a much better grip on different principles of design, and the history behind them (involving people like Edward Tufte, W.E.B. Du Bois, Florence Nightingale, Mona Chalabi). I also better understand the link between abstract art and design. To a lesser extent, I emerged with an expanded understanding of research design.
Learned to visualize data in different ways (using ggplot)
R data visualize
Ggplot, introduction to R, how to apply R to social data visualizations
Through this course, I learned how to assess the effectiveness of data visualizations in political science, as well as how to create visualizations, primarily through R.
I learned how graphs can often be improved for the better or manipulated for the worse. I also learned how to create a solid, but often basic, graph in ggplot2

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Dr. Coppock and his TAs were wonderful, engaging, thoughtful, and clearly expert on the topics presented. It was a joy to be in his class, and had one of the greatest skills/knowledge received to time commitment ratios of any class I have taken at Yale. You will learn a ton. You will apply the lessons learned to many other courses and projects.

One improvement that could be made: many of the early Psets seemed too similar (homages/redesigns/etc.) and were too focused on artistic representation rather than actual coding. I think that some of the early psets could thus be beefed up a bit.
The course was engaging and the assignments were fun.

Weakness: uploading the code for students to follow along. The one and only time the prof actually uploaded code for us to follow was probably the best class of the whole course. Otherwise, it felt very dull. Coding notes were not very good since prof would present a slide full of text and then it would disappear into the void before you could type out the first line 

Strength: very organized, very chill, very understanding. Concepts were unique and I thoroughly enjoyed learning more about R and the art of data viz.

A strength of this course is how well it manages to synthesize art, political science, statistics, and coding, exploring unique intersections that I had never thought about. Lecture is engaging, and time passes quickly - I especially enjoyed the interactive elements of lecture like the polls and oil pastels. The psets in this class are the most enjoyable homework I've ever had. I spent hours designing and redesigning just because I found the degree of freedom we were given so interesting. I will note, though, that you have to be somewhat independently motivated to get the most out of this class - the more time you spend trying to perfect a visualization (going to office hours, reading the textbook, etc), the more you will learn.

Strengths: Professor Coppock is an extremely engaging lecturer, and the material is very interesting. It also teaches you practical skills that would be very useful for anyone interested in working in quantitative fields or social science. The P-Sets are not too difficult, and often teach you a lot. I didn't feel like the class was stressful or frightening at any point, despite the fact that I was learning a ton and doing engaging work. When you're done with the class, you will know a lot more than when you came in, not have stressed too much about the class, and have P-sets full of code about how to make all sorts of useful visualizations.

Weaknesses: There is no Visualization of Political and Social Data II, the sequel to the original.

This is by far the best class I have taken at Yale so far. It is extremely engaging, and you find yourself applying the lessons from class to graphs we see in the real world everyday. The lectures are always so interesting, and 50 minutes fly by in this class.

Its main strength is Prof Coppock  hes incredibly approachable, funny, and engaging in class. In terms of weaknesses, its not organized perfectly content-wise  the material isnt really linear after the first few weeks when you learn the basics of ggplot2. There are some interesting subjects you jump around to, though, so I dont think thats a huge weakness.

Strengths: lectures were engaging and interesting. 

Weaknesses: expectations for our weekly psets were sometimes ambiguous.

Professor Coppock is a clear strength! He is a kind, interesting, passionate professor and a greater lecturer. Would strongly recommend him. But I did not learn a ton. I think Professor Coppock could add a lot more content to the class, especially in the R department. We kinda ran out of stuff to talk about. That couldve been solved by more ggplot2 and R instruction at the beginning of the semester. Im leaving this class knowing how to use ggplot2 and R, which I did not know before, but I have some MAJOR holes in my knowledge because the psets were not designed in such a way that forced you to learn and understand the ggplot2 and R concepts. But it was a cool and interesting class. Not hard at all which was nice! And Coppock is a gem!

One last thing (and this is more for Prof Coppock cause he is totally the kind of professor who cares about what students think and would read the class feedback). I would change the pset grading system. Its very kind to give us a 0,1,2 scale where you basically always get a 2 for doing the work. However, it means that any small screwup on an assignment (like forgetting to answer a problem or giving some lame answer) DRAMATICALLY impacts your grade since a 1.5 is a 75% and there arent that many psets. I would make the psets harder, require more engagement with ggplot2, and then grade them normally with a couple points for each problem.

Strengths:
- LOTS of support from TAs (Shikhar literally saved my life) and Prof Coppock
- Very interesting and engaging lectures
- Psets that help you develop your skills in R
- Useful and applicable information
- Ability to showcase your work when Prof Coppock incorporates students' assignments into the lesson

Weaknesses:
- One small thing: the first PSET was unnecessarily difficult for people just starting out using R. I spent 5 hours completing it (I had no prior coding experience) and didn't feel like I had as much support as for the other psets because I didn't know the TAs yet. All of the other psets were fun and manageable, but the first one I felt like I was scrambling, especially compared to some students who were already fluent in R

Strengths: Fantastic and iconic lecturer who did a great job making each lecture interesting and informative, really helpful TAs who taught us a lot of coding in section, great problem sets that helped us put things into practice and learn by doing. Weaknesses: Could have used a more guided rubric for the final assessment as it was left really vague and I wasn't sure what I was going to be graded on or what was expected.

Strengths: a small lecture and a great professor who cares about his students and loves about the subject area. Weaknesses: some of the topics are a bit disjoint so in the middle of the semester it's easy to lose motivation and stop going to classes.
I would have preferred exposure to more visualising software.

This course is excellent. Professor Coppock is very engaging and excited about the content. And data visualization is a very good skill to have. I think this course could be improved by having us also learn other data visualization software like tableau at the end. The end of the course as is started to feel repetitive.

The freedom and versatility of the classs subject matter greatly benefited this course. We learn quite a bit of general code which could be applied to almost any research field. The open-ended assignments allow us to really stretch the capabilities of the examples we are given. The only real downside that comes to mind is how professor Coppock doesnt always post the example code weve seen in class. They would give us a great starting point for any new projects.

Some key strengths of the course were that it contained really fascinating and fun lectures, had lots of opportunities for thinking outside-of-the box, and taught me some really valuable skills in data visualization that I will continue to use! There were no real weaknesses of this course I can think of.

Strengths: I liked learning about the theory. I thought lectures were usually pretty engaging. Really liked the incorporation of art and history. I think the workload was really balanced and wouldn't change a thing there. I think we had the chance to try things out and you could spend more time on them if you wanted to really challenge yourself. The problem sets were primarily graded on effort, which encouraged me to take risks in my visualizations that I might not have otherwise.

Weaknesses: A lot of our problem sets had the same general format (homage/redesign). Might be nice to switch it up a bit. We focused a lot on the critique of existing data visualizations. But when you are determining what kind of visualization to make for a particular applications, what are some principles/best practices that might be helpful? I think that could have been incorporated a little more. Lecture code wasn't posted for most of the class (thought this was done after student feedback later in the course). Lecture slides weren't posted for the most part. Alex tried to explain why, but I still think it would be valuable. Because there are so many visualizations in the lectures, it's hard to take notes/draw/recreate those and the key points about them. I'm completely relying on my memory, and that's not providing much detail/isn't going to last very long. It would be nice to be able to refer back to them. It would be nice if we got an introduction/motivation for the tidyverse way of organizing data.

This class was very strong in its ability to teach the basics of ggplot2. However, towards the end of the course, lessons began to feel a bit repetitive and dull because we had learned most of what we needed to know for the final project by mid-semester.
Everything is perfect! Nothing needs to be improved.
Professor is extremely understanding and clearly passionate about the material.

Prof. Coppock is an engaging, compelling lecturer. He teaches us what "he finds interesting," and more often than not, I find those things interesting too. Honestly, his lectures were highlights of my week.
Prof. Coppock not publishing his lectures served as incentive to come to class, but I would have appreciated R code (I could reexamine after class) for the new ggplot techniques covered in class. (Since we often sped through the code.)
Section was the best way to learn the R code necessary for the problem sets. Because Shikhar was so great, I always learned a lot at section. However, with a TA less adept than Shikhar (and if I was less experienced with R), the model of "learn all the technical skills necessary for the problem sets in section" may not have worked for me.
Strengths: Coppock's accessibility, entertaining lectures

This course is well-designed but is NOT easily comprehensible for someone without prior coding experience. There were not enough opportunities to learn or relearn basic R language which unfortunately compounded throughout the course and made it difficult to catch up if something was missed earlier in the year. The lectures, readings, and conceptual teaching of the class were extremely well-designed, but I believe it should require an intro coding class or provide more additional enrichment or tutoring options.

The strengths of this course are the teaching team and the topics covered. Professor Coppock is an excellent instructor that presented clear and concise lectures throughout the semester, while being receptive to student feedback, The Teaching Fellows also led great discussion sections and actively supported students with the course material through office hours and additional assistance in section. The variety in topics covered in the class also improved the learning experience.

I thought this course had some interesting lectures about Tuftes rules for visualizations and also some fun / engaging partner assignments, but I did not take away much from most lectures and thought the material was incredibly limited. I wished we got more into design principles and how they are often used by the best graphic artists today, but we mainly covered one or two graphs a lecture.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: If you want to learn data vis, then this is a no brainer. It will not go wrong. You will learn a ton. Take it.
Yes, it is a great course to give you an introduction to ggplot and to learn how to make better data visualizations. It is well taught, expectations are clear and assignments are fun.

Yeah, I felt like I thought about data viz in a new and interesting way, and I enjoyed it. I felt like this was what education was meant to be like: a place where you come, learn, and practice without all the stress.

This course is worth taking because of how interdisciplinary and different it is - take it as an artist, political scientist, or statistician, and you will find yourself learning so much about intersections of your field and other fields that you had never considered. Class is like watching a TED Talk, with fun interactive pieces that involve oil pastels or polls. I really enjoyed the readings and the problem sets - often, I found myself spending time on them not because they required it but just because they were so interesting. Many of the psets are open-ended, allowing you to tackle a visualization problem however you see fit - this feels more authentic to how visualization works in the real world (not with a professor telling you which type of graph to use but you having to figure it out for yourself). One thing I will note is that this is truly a data visualization class, so it may not be for you if you're trying to learn fancy statistical techniques or how to clean messy data.

Absolutely. This class is useful, incredibly fun, not too hard and will fill you with a passion for data visualization you had no idea you had. You will leave with useful skills; an understanding of the importance of data visualization essential to social science and statistics; and a collection of interesting takes and facts about data visualization. You will also have a great time doing it! It is possibly my favorite class I have taken at Yale.

1000%. Regardless of what your major is, data visualization will be an asset to you. Although you do learn about R and how to actually code the graphs, I think the most important takeaways from this course are how to make good visualizations. It also encourages you to think critically about your surroundings.
Yes! You learn a solid dataviz foundation in R and ggplot2 if you are engaged with the material.
Absolutely. Alex is an amazing and passionate instructor, plus the contents of class are super interesting and useful when it comes to building a better knowledge of ggplot2 and R.

Im not sure. I enjoyed the class, and I would definitely recommend Professor Coppock! But I did not learn a ton of coding  perhaps it is my mistake for assuming there would be a lot of coding. I did learn some cool history and had a fun time learning about visualization. I think Professor Coppock could add a lot more content to the class, especially in the R department. We kinda ran out of stuff to talk about. That couldve been solved by more ggplot2 and R instruction at the beginning of the semester. Im leaving this class knowing how to use ggplot2 and R, which I did not know before, but I have some MAJOR holes in my knowledge because the psets were not designed in such a way that forced you to learn and understand the ggplot2 and R concepts. But it was a cool and interesting class. Not hard at all which was nice! And Coppock is a gem!

Yes! I had 0 coding or stats experience prior to this course, and I learned SO much and ended absolutely loving it! If you are on the fence because you feel like you'll fall behind students who have more experience coding, don't be afraid. I was nervous to take this course, but I found that my inexperience actually encouraged me to be more engaged, take advantage of every resource (use office hours, email TAs, meet with Prof Coppock, listen to lecture), and I felt supported throughout the semester! Take the course, you got this!

Yes!! This is a great class that combines polisci, data science/coding, history of data visualization, and graphic design principles. You will develop a lot of practical skills to make all future ggplot graphs incredibly well-designedsomething that can be applied to almost any field of research! The lectures are all very engaging and interesting, and the problem sets are all pretty fun too. Be aware of the final project being 25% of the grade, as the rubric this semester was a little vague. If I had more time I definitely would have gone to office hours to ask more questions about it, so something to keep in mind!

Definitely! I'm an S&DS major but there are people from all sorts of background in this class so it's really nice. The 3000-word final is a natural continuation of learning and it didn't feel too stressful at all.
Yes! A low stakes way to improve r skills while creating good graphs.
Absolutely. I think anyone would benefit from taking this class and learning about data visualization in todays data driven world. Its an exciting fun class.
yes if you'd like to take it as a stats elective

Definitely! The workload is extremely fair, with weekly homework assignments that are neither mindless, nor overburdening. Many of them were geared towards how creative we could be with our knowledge of ggplot. Professor Coppock keeps lecture engaging with a completely new and exciting topic every time.

I would definitely recommend this class! It was a stress-free opportunity to learn about a critical component of statistics and was very applicable to nearly every field of research, from social science to the physical sciences. The assignments were pretty straightforward and, while they did require a fair bit of work at times, were definitely rewarding.

Yes. The material is interesting and I found lectures engaging. I appreciated the mix of theory and practical applications with respect to data visualization. I had coding and R experience, so I can't comment on what this was like as a first coding class. I usually work in base R, and I was kind of hoping to come out of this with a more balanced perspective with respect to the tidyverse, but I'm not sure that quite happened. I wish there would have been more motivation/justification for why organizing data this way is better.
Yes! I would definitely recommend this course to students who are looking to explore basic r in a political science context.
Yes! Please take it! Its one of the best courses I have taken at Yale! You will learn a lot from this class.
Yes. Great 5th course to learn an increasingly important skill in todays world.
This is simply the perfect class.

Absolutely.
Data visualization is a valuable skill for basically every academic field. And PLSC 349 has such a reasonable workload that everyone who can should add it as a 4th/5th class. (That said, the workload is negligible: psets can take as long as you want them to take, and I often spent 5+ hours on each week's pset. If you are not familiar with R, the first two psets will require that you seek out extra help.)

You will learn something new every class. Lectures are phenomenal (dense with interesting material and concise).
Yes! Professor is great and the TAs are super helpful. Super chill class and useful skills. Highly recommend!

I would recommend this course to a student who is not too familiar with data visualization, R, or statistics, who is interested in getting started! I gained a strong command of the R programming language and familiarity with all kinds of graphs and visualizations, including networks, animation, and maps! The TFs are extremely helpful and complement course material very well.
Yes! One of my favorite classes at Yale.

I would strongly recommend this course to any student who would like a great foundation to R and data visualizations more generally. This course helps students understand R, how to analyze data visualizations, and how to create the visualizations, in a very comprehensive manner. These skills are transferable to other political science courses as well.

This course is a good fifth class and straightforward way to fulfill a requirement for the data science certificate. In all honest, it is not the most rewarding, but if you remotely enjoy creating data visualizations, it can be incredibly engaging and an easier A.
